**Introduction**

From outlawing abortion to forced sterilization, the issue of pregnancy and birth is not only historically controversial but culturally polarizing. With the advancement of modern medicine and the popularization of contraception, abortion rate worldwide has declined from 4.6% in 1990 to 2.7% in 2014. However, in many places of the world, a woman&#39;s choice of terminating her embryo or fetus&#39;s life is not entirely her own to make, as cultural, religious, societal, legal and economic and influences continuously dictate whether the undertaking of this journey from womb to tomb is safe, legal, moral, or medically performable.

The World Health Organization reports an annual rate of 25 million unsafe abortions to occur worldwide, despite technology allowing the rest 55% percent of abortions to occur safely. The legality of abortions vary dramatically over different countries and cultures: some allows open and unlimited legal access, others grant limited legality on grounds of rape, incest, genetic impairment or to save a woman&#39;s life, while some outlaw abortion completely.

In this regard, the current state of limited access to safe and legal abortion rests more heavily on a moral - and at times, economic and political - impasse. &quot;Pro-life&quot; groups claim abortions to be unfair to the fetus on religious and moral grounds, while &quot;pro-choice&quot; groups put the mother&#39;s right to life and wellbeing first and foremost. Despite great variations in cultural attitudes across the globe regarding abortion, the Guttmacher Institute&#39;s study showed that abortion rates are similar across countries regardless of its legal status. Thus, the extent to which abortion is affected locally by social stigma, cultural conservativeness and religious prohibition impacts a woman&#39;s access to safe and legal abortion as well as her consequences for such actions.

There are, in addition, more facets to a woman&#39;s reproductive rights (which the United Nations define as a human right) not guaranteed to her by today&#39;s society. Issues such as access to contraception, sex education, the right to family planning as well as female genital mutilation are all concerns to be addressed to fully empower women in their contemporary lives.

**Definition of Key Terms**

_Developing baby_: After fertilization, a _zygote_ cell is formed. Generally speaking, the _zygote_ is said to develop into an _embryo_ between the first and ninth weeks of fertilization, which further develops into a _fetus_ from the tenth week onwards. However, there are no clear scientific features that separate embryos and fetuses. As the italicized terminologies are heavily costed within the abortion debate, this research report will use an umbrella term of _&quot;the developing baby&quot;_ to address the embryo or fetus in prenatal development. It is important to note that abortion procedures may differ in different stages of pregnancy and some states base their abortion legislation on when it is to occur in the pregnancy.

_Personhood:_ Defined by the Oxford Dictionary as &#39;the quality or condition of being an individual person&#39;, personhood is a heavily contested terminology within the debate regarding the morality of abortion as it is stated in relation or reference to the developing baby&#39;s consciousness, pain and others. Opinions differ on when exactly does the developing baby gains personhood and are often subject to different philosophical, cultural and religious interpretations.

_Abortion rights movements__:_ Also called _&quot;_pro-choice&quot; movements, they aim to advocate for legal and safe access to abortion services for women. These movements emphasize abortion to be a woman&#39;s own choice and empowers autonomy over a woman&#39;s own body, and may sometimes be extended to liberalizing cultural attitudes towards abortion and advocating for access to a wider range of reproductive rights such as contraception use and sex education.

_Anti-Abortion movements__:_ Also called_&quot;_pro-life&quot; movements, they advocate against legalization and access to abortion, often using moral and religious arguments. While exact opinions differ, most pro-life movements place emphasis on the right to life of the fetus on grounds of its own personhood and believes it is unjust to terminate a pregnancy. It is to be noted that different movements may advocate against abortion entirely or advocate for it to be allowed on only limited grounds (such as to save a woman&#39;s life.)

_Abortion__:_ Defined by the Oxford Dictionary as the deliberate termination of a human pregnancy. Abortion can be performed in two ways: medically (taking a pill to end the pregnancy, usually carried out before the ninth week of pregnancy) and surgically (either by vacuum aspiration, which is performed before the fifteenth week of pregnancy, in which a tube is inserted into the cervix to terminate the pregnancy, or by dilatation and evacuation, which is performed during the fifteenth week and involves another method of terminating the pregnancy through the cervix.) Aside from these common methods, other methods may be utilized later in pregnancy or in case of a woman&#39;s medical complications.

_Birth Control__:_ Also called contraceptions, birth control are methods used to prevent a pregnancy. These may include condoms, hormonal pills, sterilization, intrauterine devices and emergency medications.

**Topic Summary/ Overview**

The topic of reproductive rights has many potentials to be polarizing, personal and heavily influenced by culture. As sexuality, pregnancies and family planning are very personal matters, it is difficult to universalize the quality of sexual health and ensure reproductive rights for all women. While legal and cultural trends have been moving in support of promoting reproductive rights over the past decade, it is worthy to be noted that the topic of reproductive health and some views regarding it - notably abortion, contraception use, STIs - are still taboo culturally in many parts of the world. Despite this, the United Nations does reproductive rights to be human rights, and hence it is a universal mission to ensure their promotion.

**Abortion**

In the case of an unwanted pregnancy, a woman may choose or need to terminate her pregnancy through medical or surgical means as a result of various personal, medical and social reasons. For a more detailed account on methods of abortion, see its entry in Key Terms. As of now, access to safe and legal abortion is not universal in the world due to a range of cultural and historical reasons.

**Legality of Abortion Worldwide**
 ![]()(data:image/*;base64,)

It is to be noticed that abortion legislation follow geographical trends as similar cultures share similar views on abortion. While other nations have legalized abortion, it does not always come with equal terms. Most notably, abortion legislation around the world can be divided into the following four categories, listed from the least restrictive to the most restrictive:

_Legal on request, no restriction on reason:_ a woman may legally request abortion for any reason. (Legislation in: East Asia, Europe, North America and Southern African Regions. 61 countries)

_Legal on grounds of socioeconomic reasons, fetal impairment, rape or incest, to preserve a woman&#39;s mental health, to preserve a woman&#39;s life_: a woman may undergo abortion for some or all of the above list of reasons. These legislation take into account of broader socioeconomic factors that may not enable a woman to start a family, albeit there is a restriction place on reason.(Legislation in: Europe, Central America, South East Asia. 14 countries)

_Legal on grounds of preserving a woman&#39;s life or physical and mental health:_ a woman&#39;s own will does not decide whether she is allowed abortion, but her health situation does. Some countries exclude the mental health as a grounds for abortion to only take into account physical conditions of the woman. (Legislation in: Africa, South America. 60 countries.)

_Legal to save a woman&#39;s life:_ abortion is allowed only if the pregnancy becomes life-threatening to the woman. (Legislation in: South East Asia, Middle East, West Africa. 38 countries)

_Illegal completely:_ a woman cannot opt for abortion. (Legislation in: Africa, South America, South East Asia. 26 countries)

Additionally, country may place late-term restrictions on abortions: that is, women are not able to opt for abortion after a certain point in pregnancy. Also, countries may require a woman to acquire doctor&#39;s permission or receive counseling before deciding to opt for abortion.

Recently, abortion legislation in Ireland, Argentina and United States came into discussion regarding modification. For results of these modifications, refer to their entries in Major Parties Involved.

**Safety and Access**

On average, 56 million abortions occur each year out of 211 million pregnancies: a quarter of all pregnancies end in abortion. Out of the total number of abortions, 25 million occurred unsafely, almost all in developing countries. WHO notes that over half of these unsafe abortions occurred in Asia, while the risk of dying from an unsafe abortion is the highest in Africa - 62% of deaths relating to unsafe abortions occur there. Unsafe conditions occur in unregulated clinics or local establishments where the personnel might be poorly trained, using outdated or unsterilized equipment, or using outdated methods of abortion. As a result of an unsafe condition for abortion, women may experience complications including incomplete abortion, infection and damage to the reproductive system, while in extreme cases women may experience haemorrhage and severe infection which may lead to death. 68000 deaths occur annually from unsafe abortions. It is noted that deaths and complications due to unsafe abortions could be prevented by providing access to legal and safe abortions regardless of age, marital status, reason and economic circumstance, as well as reducing social stigma of abortion.

There are many factors that cause unsafe abortions. In countries where abortion is illegal, alternative medicine and underground clinics provide unsafe methods of abortion, which are often poorly staffed and use old, unclean equipment and methods, especially in circumstances where women live in remote regions with underdeveloped medical technology and cultural/traditional methods of abortion. However, even if abortion is legal in a country, some women still opt for clandestine abortion in illegal clinics due to economic or social pressures. Healthcare providers who hold anti-abortion views may refuse to cover abortion costs, while social stigma (especially in unmarried women and women not of legal age) force some women to undergo abortion in illicit clinics alone.

It is worthwhile to note that physical safety is not the only concern during and post abortion. A woman&#39;s psychological state may be traumatized by the procedure especially in an environment where abortion may place shame or other negative connotations on her identity and reputation.

**Cultural and Religious**  **Barriers**** to **** Abortion **** Access**

Multiple cultures and religions offer their own views on abortion, which may limit access in countries where those religions or cultures are majority since most people would be following the teachings of said culture or religion regarding abortion. The following are some of the major religious interpretations of abortion and their geographical reaches.

Buddhism: Buddhism is most popular in South East Asia and East Asia. The majority of Buddhists believe that abortion is acceptable if it is in the interest of protecting a mother&#39;s life and health.

Islam: Islam is most popular in Middle East and North Africa. Islam beliefs state that &quot;a child gains a soul&quot; after 16 weeks of pregnancy and teaches that abortion is only to be allowed up to that period, and afterwards only in protection of a mother&#39;s life.

Christianity: refer to entries of Ireland and Argentina in Major Parties involved.

Culturally, abortion is generally stigmatized in many areas of the world due to various reasons. 58% of pregnant Americans believe that they need to keep the abortion secret from friends and families: abortion is not only a personal matter, but a topic open to judgement and controversy as well due to some of the factors listed below.

Fetal personification: Technology such as ultrasound scans have allowed for more detailed views of the fetus and fueled discussions on whether fetus has &#39;personhood&#39;, with some groups equating abortion to murder and casts stigma on the woman who chooses to terminate the pregnancy.

Purity/idealistic womanhood: A woman who seeks abortion could be regarded as promiscuous if she is below the legal age of consent or unmarried. Shame and social pressures from family units, workplaces and educational institutions sometimes force these women to undergo clandestine, unsafe abortions as well as suffer the consequences of abortion in the form of social commentary.

Criticism/social responsibility: In many parts of the world, women are criticized for their decision to undergo abortion directly and frequently, sometimes by their closest friends and family and even the doctors and nurses who provide the abortion service. General criticism regarding the unintended pregnancy, such as why had the woman got pregnant in the first place or why had she chosen to commit an abortion (where abortion is viewed negatively), led many women to feel that abortion is a traumatic event in their lives.

**Other Reproductive Rights of Wome**** n**

Apart from access to safe and legal abortion, there are many areas of reproductive health that could be improved globally. Better access to birth control, sex education and gender equality can allow a woman to truly take control of her own body and her reproductive rights.

**Access to Birth Control**

Birth control is the practice of preventing unwanted pregnancies by the use of contraception. For a technical definition, refer to its entry in Key Terms. In 2015, 64% of women of reproductive age around the world are using some form of contraception. The most common methods of contraception vary greatly around the world across countries, with dominant methods the contraception pill, injectables and IUD and less commonly used methods being female sterilization, male condoms or other traditional methods. Some methods of contraception may also prevent the spread of sexually transmitted diseases.

However, there is an unmet need for family planning - at least 10% of women who want to delay pregnancy are not using contraception. According to a report published by the UN Department of Economic and Social Affairs Population Division, contraceptive use is much lower in
 ![]()(data:image/*;base64,)

 developing countries and particularly in Africa, where only 33% of women use contraceptives. It is also in Sub-Saharan Africa that the unmet need for family planning is the greatest - 24.2%.  According to the WHO, this unmet need could be attributed to economic reasons, a limited choice of methods,

 ![]()(data:image/*;base64,)

 experience of side-effects or fear, limited access due to population reasons(adolescents, poor, unmarried), cultural or religious opposition, and quality of contraception. The same report projected growth in contraception usage to 2030, and emphasized the need for awareness regarding contraception and the governmental responsibility to make contraception readily available to all members of the population.

It is to be noted that the use of contraception decreases the rate of abortions, deaths of mother and children and promotes the right of family planning - the right to decide the spacing and number of one&#39;s children. It is paramount that family planning services are being offered to all sectors of society.

Another note is that modern contraception methods, while varied and mostly effective, usually involves women to take the initiative and in turn costs them the most in terms of effort, time and money. However, more new methods of contraception are being developed (e.g. March 2018, the male contraceptive pill) and it is potentially possible to adapt the type of contraception used to a person&#39;s need even more in the future.

**Sex Education**

Sex education refers to the education on issues regarding sexuality(such as developments in the adolescent body, contraceptive use, pregnancies, and sexually transmitted diseases) which is usually provided by parents or school systems. However, sex education remains a taboo topic for many households and schools, especially in culturally conservative nations or regions where sex itself is a taboo topic, despite the need to discuss it to prevent ignorance that would lead to unintended pregnancies and sexually transmitted diseases.

There are many types of sex education: some are formal while others are not, and incorrect statements as well as cherry-picking-data-manipulation regarding reproductive health may be spread during sex education to prevent the adolescents from having sex. Abstinence-only sex education involves the instruction of not having sex unless one is married, however this has found to be ineffective in reducing unwanted pregnancies and HIV infections.

There are limited data on the number of countries offering compulsory, state-sponsored sex education as well as the content of such courses, if any. As an example, in China and India, the world&#39;s two most populated countries, sex education is taboo and such topics are meant to elicit shame in youths. Modesty is promoted and parents are reluctant to educate their children, and children may grow up to adulthood without any formal exposure to sex education.

 It is shown that the positive effects of a comprehensive, informative sex education not only excels in preventing unwanted pregnancies but empowers young adults in taking control of their own reproductive rights. Reducing the rate of infection of sexually transmitted diseases, stopping sexual abuse, and understanding consent not only helps young people to learn about a crucial aspect of human life but also allows them to protect themselves physically and mentally.

**Major Parties Involved**

**Ireland**

Located in northwestern Europe, approximately 78% of the Republic of Ireland&#39;s population is religiously Roman Catholic. Abortion is frowned upon traditionally in Catholic teachings, as it is believed that abortion equals to murdering an unborn child that God has given the parents. With this religious background, the Eighth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland was passed in Ireland in 1983 and forbade abortion by recognizing that the right to life of the unborn is equalto that of the mother and restricts abortion to only be allowed if a woman&#39;s life was in danger.

Until 2018, there has been no major changes to the amendment despite heavy activism in opposition of it both domestically and globally. However, during the beginning of 2018, discussions began in parliament regarding modifying the legislation in a bill that will allow for abortion without specific reason given to up to 12 weeks of pregnancy and also for medical emergencies, abnormal fetal condition and danger to a woman&#39;s life. On 25th of May, 2018, a referendum was hosted to, essentially, gather public opinion on whether abortion should be allowed or not. The aforementioned bill passed overwhelmingly with 66.4% of voters voting yes.

**Argentina**

Argentina is a nation located in South America where 77.1% of its population is Roman Catholic by religion. For Catholic teachings on abortion, please refer to the entry on Ireland. Abortion is illegal in Argentina except in circumstances where a woman&#39;s life is threatened.

In comparison with Ireland, Argentina&#39;s abortion legislation also entered into heavy debate in 2018. On August 8th 2018, the Argentinian Senate rejected a bill which would legalized abortion to up to 14 weeks into the pregnancy without a specific reason given despite heavy social activism in support of the bill. It is to be noted that the bill was rejected by a marginal vote of 31 votes in support and 38 votes in opposition.

**United States**

Abortion is a very controversial issue in the United States, where the case of Roe vs. Wade is a legal landmark on which the abortion legislation in the U.S. is based currently. Different states apply different legislation which reflects the range of different views regarding abortion. The President of the United States had claimed himself to be both pro-life and pro-choice on the same occasion during the presidential election of 2016. As of now, 43 out of 50 states prohibit abortion after a certain time point in pregnancy and 35 states require a woman to receive counseling before abortion is approved. &quot;Pro-life&quot; and &quot;pro-choice&quot; debates are heavy in the U.S. in an effort to alter legislation.

In June, Iowa banned abortion after a fetal heartbeat is detected - which could be as early as 6 weeks into pregnancy. In November 2018, Alabama will vote on amending its constitution regarding protecting &quot;unborn children,&quot; essentially whether or not to cut funding on abortion.

**World Health Organization**** (WHO)**

The World Health Organization is a United Nations organization that promotes and supports public health worldwide. It has published multiple research papers and programs regarding the current state of unsafe abortions worldwide and the state of reproductive health in general.

While the WHO has not taken a political stance on the legalization of abortions, it implied that unsafe abortions occur as a result of illegality in various publications.

**The Guttmacher Institute**

The Guttmacher Institute is a research and policy non-governmental organization that concerns itself with advancing sexual and reproductive rights globally, with a focus in the United States. Its three main areas of development are &quot;High quality research, evidence-based advocacy and strategic communications.&quot; It was founded in 1968 as a subdivision of Planned Parenthood, a reproductive health care service provider in the U.S.,  but became independent in 1977 despite having received funding from it.

The Guttmacher Institute analyzed and collected data on unsafe abortions globally and concerns itself with supporting legalization of abortion and safety of abortion in the United States and worldwide(including through U.S. foreign aid). Apart from abortion, some of the Institute&#39;s major areas of research are contraception, HIV &amp; STIS, pregnancies in general and teen reproductive health.

**Previous UN Involvement**

**UN Resolutions**

There has been no UN resolutions that specifically address the improvement of reproductive rights in general or the access to safe and legal abortion.

**Preventable maternal mortality and morbidity and human rights** (A/HRC/RES/33/18): The resolution touches somewhat on the matter of abortion. Apart from discussing unsafe abortion in its preambulatory clauses, it calls for &quot;states to take steps to ensure that laws, policies and practices respect women&#39;s equal right to decide autonomously in matters regarding their own lives and health by repealing discriminatory laws and combating gender stereotypes and behaviours that discriminate against them.&quot;

**Elimination of discrimination against women** (A/HRC/RES/32/4) **and**  **Accelerating efforts to eliminate violence against women** (A/HRC/RES/32/19): Both resolutions urge states to promote reproductive rights of women, including &quot;safe and effective methods of modern contraception, emergency contraception, prevention programs for adolescent pregnancy&quot; as well as &quot;safe abortion where such services are permitted by national law.&quot;

**Rights of the child: the right of the child to the enjoyment of the highest attainable standard of health** **(**A/HRC/RES/22/32**):** The resolution addresses improving the sexual and reproductive health of children and adolescents in one of its clauses, highlighted here as a quote: &quot;…to provide quality services for the management of complications arising from abortion, and, in circumstances where abortion is not against the law, training and equipping health service providers and other measures to ensure that such abortion is safe and accessible.&quot;

**Intensifying global efforts for the elimination of female genital mutilation** (A/RES/71/168): This resolution addresses the efforts for elimination of FGM globally in developing legislative networks, increasing awareness, and promoting social changes at local levels.

**UN Organizational Efforts**

Several UN organizations are working towards the promotion of reproductive rights at actionable and cultural levels.

**United Nations Human Rights Committee** **(UNHRC)**

The UNHRC has been working to empower the rights of women and girls, and in turn reproductive health is an aspect of their work in this area. The UNHRC has passed various resolutions urging states to improve reproductive rights, including access to health services and contraception. However, past UNHRC resolutions suggest access to safe abortion if &quot;such services are permitted by national law.&quot; Nevertheless, the Office of the High Commissioner of Human Rights state that &quot;international human rights bodies stated generally criminalizing abortion is discriminatory and a barrier to women&#39;s access to health care.&quot;

While reproductive rights were not explicitly stated in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (and subsequently, statements from the UDHR were interpreted differently by various groups to support their differing stances on abortion), the UNHRC decided that right to medically necessary abortion is a human right in 2016, through ruling a case that Peruvian government must pay reparations to a woman who was denied an abortion in a circumstance where her life might have been threatened.

The UNHRC also holds reproductive rights in high importance regarding situations concerning refugees and indigenous peoples, resulting in 1 resolution and several field manuals regarding implementing and promoting reproductive health in these situations.

**UN Women**

UN Women is &quot;the UN organization dedicated to gender equality and the empowerment of women.&quot; While access to reproductive rights are not directly stated in its strategic priorities, UN Women has championed a woman&#39;s right over her own body and has worked on helping women to cope and prevent HIV/AIDS and offered medical services to women in various field locations.

In a press release, it is stated that UN Women &quot;do not promote abortion as a method of family planning&quot; but remains in supportive of &quot;women&#39;s and girls&#39; rights around the world.&quot;

**United Nations Population Fund**** (UNFPA)**

UNFPAis the United Nations sexual and reproductive health agency, stating its mission to be &quot;a world in which every pregnancy is wanted, every childbirth is safe and every young person&#39;s potential is fulfilled.&quot; It supports &quot;reproductive health care for women and youth in more than 150 countries, reliable access to modern contraceptives sufficient to benefit 20 million women a year, abandonment of female genital mutilation, prevention of teen pregnancies, delivery of safe birth supplies, dignity kits and other life-saving materials to survivors of conflict and natural disaster.&quot;

One of its major areas of work is family planning, in which UNFPA works to ensure the availability of safe contraceptives around the world, especially in less economically developed countries.

**Possible Solutions**

Training medical personnel: Could the safety of abortions worldwide be improved if medical personnel&#39;s training are centralized? Should medical personnel at local levels be trained to be proficient with general knowledge regarding abortion and reproductive rights so they could act as local counsellors to those who need help? Is this especially needed in less developed countries? Is this the UN&#39;s job or the local government&#39;s job and if it is the latter, how could one ensure the uniformity of training across countries? Is this uniformity even necessary?

Ensuring quality and safety of service: If a legal abortion system does not exist or if the woman&#39;s situation prevents her from seeking legal abortion (Social stigma? Medical insurance/too expensive? Too late in term?), she may turn to underground clinics or alternative medicine with compromised safety. Should governments oversee the quality of abortion services provided in order to ensure their safety? Should they eradicate such rogue abortion clinics?

Availability of contraception: Studies have shown that availability of contraception decreases abortion rates. If many methods of contraception is readily available, there will be less unintended pregnancies. Should governments decrease tax on contraception or make some methods complimentary to its citizens? Should some methods of contraception cease to be a prescription drug and become over-the-counter instead?

Legalize abortion: In some countries, abortion is illegal. In others, abortion is legal in only certain circumstances (e.g. rape, child with disability, life-threatening for mother.) Legalizing abortion ensures that women have access to this fundamental reproductive right.

Cultural change/destigmatization: Abortion is stigmatized in many countries. In many parts of the world, women suffer social consequences for unintended pregnancies and abortions, especially if she is not married. Depending on the culture of the country, a woman may be criticized for abortion and asking for access to birth control and at times, whether to terminate a pregnancy may not be entirely her choice. Hence, even if legal method of abortion are available, a woman may suffer psychologically because of the culture around her. Destigmatising abortion and empowering women to take control of their own bodies and their own reproductive rights may be difficult to carry out in many cultures. Is it necessary? Is it workable in all parts of the world and all sections of societies? Does a woman&#39;s reproductive decisions matter in the context of decreasing unintended pregnancies? Is cultural change important regarding improving reproductive rights of women?

Sex education/general awareness: If women and girls are more informed about pregnancies and the methods of contraception available to them, there would be fewer unintended pregnancies. An increase of general awareness also empowers women to take ownership of their reproductive rights. Should sex education be included as a part of the national curriculum? Should sex education be abstinence-only? Should sex education include the possibility of abortion and the use of contraceptives? How could awareness of contraceptive methods or general sex education be impacted by the culture of the country?
